doc.ContractDescription: MESOPELAGIC FISHES ARE THE MOST ABUNDANT VERTEBRATES ON THE PLANET AND FORM DENSE LAYERS BETWEEN 200-1,000 M CALLED DEEP SCATTERING LAYERS (DSLS). NEARLY EVERY MARINE PREDATOR THAT HAS BEEN STUDIED WITH ELECTRONIC TAGS HAS EXHIBITED BEHAVIOR THAT SUGGESTS ASSOCIATION WITH DSLS, BUT FURTHER INFERENCE HAS BEEN CONSTRAINED BY TECHNOLOGICAL LIMITATIONS. MESOSCALE EDDIES, LARGE SWIRLING BODIES OF WATER WITH HORIZONTAL SCALE ON THE ORDER OF 100 KM, ARE A COMMON FEATURE OF THE WORLD OCEAN, COVERING NEARLY 30% OF THE OCEAN SURFACE AT ANYTIME. EDDIES INFLUENCE PRIMARY PRODUCTION IN THE OCEAN IN NUMEROUS WAYS, INCLUDING GENERATING UPWELLING AND DOWNWELLING AND TRANSPORTING ECOSYSTEMS OVER LARGE DISTANCES. HOWEVER, THE INFLUENCE OF EDDIES (AND OTHER IMPORTANT MESOSCALE FEATURES) ON MESOPELAGIC FISHES, APEX MARINE PREDATORS, AND DSLS ARE COMPLETELY UNKNOWN. THE GOAL OF THIS RESEARCH IS TO ELUCIDATE HOW PELAGIC PREDATORS ASSOCIATE WITH AND ARE INFLUENCED BY MESOSCALE FEATURES THROUGH THE SYNERGISTIC ANALYSIS OF INDIVIDUAL SHARK MOVEMENTS AND CONCURRENT SATELLITE OBSERVATIONS OF MESOSCALE EDDIES, MEANDERS, AND FRONTS IN THE OCEAN. THESE EFFORTS LEVERAGE NASA CAPABILITIES TO EXPAND OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE STRUCTURE AND FUNCTION OF THE PELAGIC OCEAN AND THE BIOPHYSICAL INTERACTIONS THAT LINK THE DEEP OCEAN TO THE EPIPELAGIC. THE RESEARCH PROPOSED HEREIN DIRECTLY FULFILLS NASA S MISSION TO DRIVE ADVANCES IN SCIENCE TO ENHANCE KNOWLEDGE, EDUCATION, INNOVATION, ECONOMIC VITALITY, AND STEWARDSHIP OF EARTH AND TO ADVANCE KNOWLEDGE OF EARTH AS A SYSTEM TO MEET THE CHALLENGES OF ENVIRONMENTAL CHANGE, AND TO IMPROVE LIFE ON OUR PLANET. ADDITIONALLY, THIS WORK IS DIRECTLY APPLICABLE TO THE EARTH SYSTEM SCIENCE DIVISION S COMMITMENT TO UTILIZING NASA S UNIQUE CAPABILITIES TO MEASURE A COMPREHENSIVE SUITE OF EARTH SYSTEM COMPONENTS AND SPECIFICALLY EXPLOITS THESE FOR A DEEPLY INTERDISCIPLINARY PROJECT GROUNDED IN UNDERSTANDING ENIGMATIC ECOSYSTEMS.
